In [10]:
cont_feature_list =["net_price", 'num1', 'num2', 'num3', 'num4', 'num5', "num6"]
fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=1, nrows=len(cont_feature_list),figsize=(15,15))
for cont_feature, ax  in zip(cont_feature_list, axes.flat):
    sns.distplot(stats.boxcox(total_df[cont_feature].add(eps))[0],label="coxbox",ax=ax)
    sns.distplot(np.log(total_df[cont_feature].add(eps)), label="log",ax=ax)
    # sns.distplot(np.sqrt(total_df[cont_feature].add(eps)), label="sqrt",ax=ax)
    kurt = stats.kurtosis(total_df[cont_feature])
    ax.set_title(f"{cont_feature} kurtosis: {kurt}")
    ax.legend()
plt.subplots_adjust(top=2) 
plt.show()

Some Observations¶

  • ## Numeric values have high kurtosis. Boxcox, sqrt, log transform can be useful. Boxcox seems to be the best.
  • ## Data is highly imbalaced. Click + purchase rate is very low.
  • ## Problem can be divided into two parts: Predict Purchase Prob and Predict Revenue. Later, they are combied.
  • ## In some numerical values, there is a high correlation.
  • ## Weekday can be added as a one-hot encoding.
  • ## Month shows some variation, but Christmas like Holidays may cause this. Also, we do not have enough knowledge and other month for prediction.
  • ## Cat variables can be merged. Maybe if they are dependent variables like city, town, street, it can be useful.
